erman <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Halstad","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Sophus, Tor.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads named Holstad, from <i>Hol-</i> (probably derived from a personal name such as Old Norse <i>Hávarthr</i>, <i>Ólafr</i>) + <i>-stad</i> from <i>stathir</i> ‘farmstead, dwelling’."],"variants":[{"name":"Holsted","meanings":["Norwegian: variant of   Holstad  . The surname <i>Holsted</i> is rare in Norway.","Probably also English: variant of   Halstead  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert De Halstad was born in 1185, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard De Halstad, was 25 and his mother, Mrs. Richard De Halstad, was 25. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. Robert Halstad."},"et":{"1185–":"1185–Surnud","1185–Male":"1185–Surnud","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","12